  filter(Country == "Australia") %>%

print_retail <- aus_retail %>%
  filter(Industry == "Newspaper and book retailing") %>%
  group_by(Industry) %>%
  index_by(Year = year(Month)) %>%
  summarise(Turnover = sum(Turnover))
aus_economy <- global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "AUS")
print_retail %>%
  left_join(aus_economy, by = "Year") %>%
  mutate(Adjusted_turnover = Turnover / CPI * 100) %>%
  pivot_longer(c(Turnover, Adjusted_turnover),
               values_to = "Turnover") %>%
  mutate(name = factor(name,
         levels = c("Turnover", "Adjusted_turnover"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Turnover)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(name ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Turnover: Australian print media industry",
       y = "$AU")

STL decomposition

us_retail_employment %>%
  model(
    STL(Employed ~ trend(window = 7) +
                   season(window = "periodic"),
    robust = TRUE)) %>%
  components() %>%
  autoplot()

  1. Transformations

Note: Id be a bit careful with transformations. Maybe do this based on an analysis of residuals from a regression, in the future. Plus, these transformations wont be as interpretable as logs.

Remember that the transformation is done to make the magnitude of the seasonal variation more uniform.

global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "United States") %>%
  autoplot(GDP)

global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "United States") %>%
  mutate(
    GDP = box_cox(
      x = GDP,
      lambda = get_boxcox_lambda(., "GDP")
    )
  ) %>%
  autoplot(GDP)

We get a slightly more linear variable. Id rather just take the log.

aus_livestock %>%
  filter(Animal == "Bulls, bullocks and steers", State == "Victoria") %>%
  autoplot(Count)

Not sure a transformation will be useful here, but I may be wrong.

aus_livestock %>%
  filter(Animal == "Bulls, bullocks and steers", State == "Victoria") %>%
  mutate(Count = box_cox(
    x = Count,
    lambda = get_boxcox_lambda(., "Count")
    )
  ) %>%
  autoplot(Count)

Probably useless here.

vic_elec %>%
  autoplot(Demand)

No point in doing anything here. There does not seem to be any trend, and the variable is highly non-linear.

  2. 3x5-MA = 7-MA with weights

5-MA:

\[ MA_t = \frac{1}{5}(y_{t-2} + y_{t-1} + y_t + y_{t+1} + y_{t+2}) \]

3x5-MA:

\[ \frac{1}{3}(\frac{1}{5}MA_{t-1} + \frac{1}{5}MA_{t} + \frac{1}{5}MA_{t+1}) \\ = \frac{1}{15}MA_{t-1} + \frac{1}{15}MA_{t} + \frac{1}{15}MA_{t+1} \\ = \frac{1}{15}y_{t-3} + \frac{2}{15}y_{t-2} + \frac{3}{15}y_{t-1} + \frac{3}{15}y_t + \frac{3}{15}y_{t+1} + \frac{2}{15}y_{t+2} + \frac{1}{15}y_{t+3} \]

  2. Canadian gas

canadian_gas %>%

Indeed: low seasonality in the 60s, quite higher in the mid-70S to 80s. There is still a bit of seasonality after that.

canadian_gas %>%
  gg_subseries()
## Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `y = Volume`

canadian_gas %>%
  model(
    STL(Volume ~ trend(window = 18) +
                   season(window = 6),
    robust = TRUE)) %>%
  components() %>%
  autoplot()

Maybe there is a metric or some indicator to correctly choose the time window. A 6-month window allows us to see the evolution of seasonality over the years quite nicely.

canadian_gas %>%
  model(
    STL(Volume ~ trend(window = 18) +
                   season(window = 6),
    robust = TRUE)) %>%
  components() %>%
  select(Month, season_year) %>%
  gg_season()
## Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `y = season_year`

Nice. Production gets increasingly lower in February and November through the years. It seems to have increased in July and August (during colder months of winter, then). Sometimes, the variation is not linear: production was lower in the early 1960s, increased rapidly in the 70s to 80s, and then decreased a little bit (e.g.January and December)

canadian_gas %>%

It seems ok. I have tried to change the window settings, but they dont seem to change the trend that drastically.

x11 and SEATS are quite similar to my untrained eyes, to be fair. I guess there are some subtleties in each that make them more efficient in specific situations. For now, both seem good. See Seasonal Adjustment Methods and Real Time Trend-cycle Estimation for a discussion about it.
